{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565157"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:23:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:23:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17271"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17271"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.78,0.08,0.1,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9961"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69789"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9961"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17271"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55244"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3831"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23348"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23427"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23428"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44811"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69789"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a non-healing ulcer on his penis. He initially thought it was a minor injury but became concerned when it did not heal. He denies pain, discharge, or bleeding. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is a retired builder who lives with his wife.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 2 cm irregular, indurated ulcer on the glans penis with rolled edges and a warty appearance (Image). The base appears fixed to underlying tissue. The lesion is not tender. There are several firm, fixed lymph nodes palpable in the right groin measuring up to 3 cm in diameter. The left groin nodes are not palpable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Penile squamous cell carcinoma","Chancroid","Primary syphilis","Herpes simplex infection","Lichen sclerosus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of penile cancer. \u003Cstrong\u003EPenile squamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as an indurated, irregular ulcer with rolled edges on the glans or prepuce. The presence of fixed inguinal lymphadenopathy suggests advanced disease. The chronic nature and lack of healing are also characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChancroid\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus ducreyi\u003C/em\u003E, typically presents as painful, soft ulcers with undermined edges and tender lymphadenopathy. The ulcers are usually multiple and appear within days to weeks of exposure. The chronicity and induration in this case make chancroid unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary syphilis\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a chancre - a painless, clean-based ulcer with smooth edges. While also painless, syphilitic chancres typically heal spontaneously within 3-6 weeks even without treatment. The indurated base and rolled edges are not typical of syphilis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex infection\u003C/strong\u003E presents with painful vesicles that ulcerate and heal within 2-3 weeks. The lesions are typically superficial and multiple. The chronic, single, indurated lesion in this case is not consistent with herpes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELichen sclerosus\u003C/strong\u003E presents with white, atrophic patches that may develop erosions or fissures. While it can be associated with penile SCC, the presentation here is more consistent with established malignancy rather than the inflammatory changes of lichen sclerosus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for penile cancer include smoking, poor hygiene, chronic inflammation, and HPV infection. The presence of fixed inguinal nodes is a poor prognostic indicator, highlighting the importance of early recognition and referral.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Penile squamous cell carcinoma commonly presents as a painless lesion on the glans or prepuce.","Inguinal lymph node examination is critical in the staging of penile cancer.","Early referral to a urologist is essential for suspected penile malignancy."],"references":["Downes MR. Review of in situ and invasive penile squamous cell carcinoma and associated non-neoplastic dermatological conditions. Journal of Clinical Pathology. 2015 May 1;68(5):333\u201340."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55244"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17271"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21299"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21299"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/PSuNTpszdHx4tqEWZeNJqUGEw4iSuP.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/PSuNTpszdHx4tqEWZeNJqUGEw4iSuP.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":540}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55244","links":{"self":"https://a